<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

 <exercise label="mcq2dvectorfielddefinition">
  <title>Understanding the Vector Field</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For a two-dimensional linear system <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>, what does the
      vector field in the phase plane represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          At each point <m>\vec{x}</m>, the vector field assigns the direction
          vector <m>P\vec{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The flow direction at each point in the
          plane is given by <m>P\vec{x}</m>. 
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>It assigns the length <m>\|\vec{x}\|</m> at each point.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. Vector fields assign direction vectors, not lengths.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>It assigns the scalar <m>\det(P)</m> to every point.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. The determinant plays a role in stability, not in defining the field.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise> 

<exercise label="mcq2dequilibrium">
  <title>Identifying the Equilibrium Point</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the homogeneous linear system <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>, what is the
      equilibrium point?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. In a homogeneous system, the equilibrium is the solution to
          <m>P\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m>, which is typically only the origin.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\vec{x} = \vec{v}_1</m>, where <m>\vec{v}_1</m> is any eigenvector.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. Eigenvectors describe trajectory directions, not equilibria.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>Every point in the plane is an equilibrium.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. That occurs only in the trivial zero matrix system.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq2dclassificationeigenvalues">
  <title>Classifying the Equilibrium</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the system <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m> where
      <m>
        P =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          3 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 1
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      How is the equilibrium at the origin classified?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An unstable node.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Both eigenvalues <m>3</m> and <m>1</m> are positive real numbers,
          so solutions grow away from the origin along eigenvector directions,
          forming an unstable node.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A saddle point.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. A saddle requires one positive and one negative eigenvalue.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A center.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. Centers require purely imaginary eigenvalues.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-phase-plane-images">
  <title>Choose the Correct Phase Plane</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the system
      <m>
        \vec{x}' =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          3 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        \vec{x}.
      </m>
      Which of the following phase portraits corresponds to this system?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="no">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><strong>(A)</strong> Unstable node</p>
      
      <figure xml:id="fig-unstable-node-img">
        <image source="images/unstable-node.svg" width="42%"/>
        <caption>Phase portrait (A): Trajectories flow out along eigen-directions.</caption>
      </figure>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Both eigenvalues are positive (<m>3</m> and <m>1</m>) so the origin
          is an <em>unstable node</em>; trajectories move outward along the eigenvector
          directions (the coordinate axes).
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><strong>(B)</strong> Saddle</p>
      
      <figure xml:id="fig-saddle-img">
        <image source="images/saddle.svg" width="42%"/>
        <caption>Phase portrait (B): Saddle structure (in/out along different axes).</caption>
      </figure>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not this one. A saddle requires eigenvalues of opposite signs, which is not
          the case here.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><strong>(C)</strong> Center</p>
      
      <figure xml:id="fig-center-img">
        <image source="images/center.svg" width="42%"/>
        <caption>Phase portrait (C): Closed orbits (center).</caption>
      </figure>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not this one. Centers correspond to purely imaginary eigenvalues (no real part),
          whereas both eigenvalues here are positive and real.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

  <!-- PROBLEM 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="twodim-open-1">
    <title>Describing the Vector Field and Trajectory Behavior</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the two-dimensional linear system
        <m>
          \vec{x}' =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            -2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp -5
          \end{bmatrix}
          \vec{x}.
        </m>
        (a) Describe the vector field in the phase plane, including how the
        direction vectors <m>P\vec{x}</m> behave at various points.
        <br/>
        (b) Classify the equilibrium at the origin and explain the qualitative 
        behavior of trajectories as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <strong>(a)</strong>  
        The vector field assigns to each point <m>(x_1,x_2)</m> the direction 
        vector <m>P\vec{x} = (-2x_1,\,-5x_2)</m>.  
        Because each component is a negative multiple of the coordinate,  
        arrows everywhere in the plane point <em>toward</em> the origin.  
        Along the <m>x_1</m>-axis, the flow is horizontal toward the origin 
        at a rate proportional to <m>-2x_1</m>.  
        Along the <m>x_2</m>-axis, the flow is vertical toward the origin but 
        at a faster rate proportional to <m>-5x_2</m>.  
        Off the axes, arrows point diagonally inward, with the 
        <m>x_2</m>-component shrinking more quickly due to the larger magnitude 
        eigenvalue.  
        This interpretation follows the definition of the vector field 
        as assigning <m>P\vec{x}</m> to each point. 
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>(b)</strong>  
        The eigenvalues of <m>P</m> are <m>-2</m> and <m>-5</m>, both negative.  
        According to the classification in Section 7.5, a system with two negative 
        real eigenvalues has a <em>stable node</em> at the origin.  
        Hence all trajectories approach the origin as <m>t \to \infty</m>.  
        Because <m>-5</m> has larger magnitude, the <m>x_2</m>-component decays 
        faster, so trajectories tilt toward the <m>x_1</m>-axis as they approach 
        the origin.  
        This is consistent with the node behavior described in the section.  
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- PROBLEM 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="twodim-open-2">
    <title>Classifying a System Using Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the system
        <m>
          \vec{x}' =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp -4 \\
            1 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          \vec{x}.
        </m>
        (a) Compute the eigenvalues and classify the equilibrium at the origin.
        <br/>
        (b) Based on the eigenvalues and eigenvectors, describe qualitatively 
        what the phase portrait looks like (e.g., rotation, spiraling, or 
        approach/escape behavior).
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <strong>(a)</strong>  
        The characteristic equation is  
        <m>
          \det\!\left(
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp -4 \\
            1 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          - \lambda I
          \right)
          =
          \det
          \begin{bmatrix}
            -\lambda \amp -4 \\
            1 \amp -\lambda
          \end{bmatrix}
          = \lambda^2 + 4 = 0.
        </m>
        Therefore the eigenvalues are <m>\lambda = \pm 2i</m>, a pair of 
        purely imaginary conjugates.  
        Purely imaginary eigenvalues correspond to a 
        <em>center</em> at the origin.  
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>(b)</strong>  
        With purely imaginary eigenvalues, solutions neither grow nor decay in 
        magnitude.  Instead, they rotate in closed or nearly closed orbits around 
        the origin.  The vector field shows arrows tangent to ellipses or circles, 
        depending on the eigenvector geometry.  
        In this case, the system behaves like a constant‑speed rotation, so the 
        phase portrait consists of closed curves (center behavior).  
        Such systems have trajectories that circle 
        the equilibrium rather than approaching or diverging from it.  
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


